## 2. First-time setup (one-time per project)

### 2.1 Accounts you need

- **Hetzner Cloud** — https://accounts.hetzner.com/ (free signup; pay-as-
  you-go, ~€4/mo for a cx23 + IPv4).
- **HCP Terraform** — https://app.terraform.io/ (free tier is fine; we
  use it for state-only).
- **GitHub** — repo at `${GITHUB_OWNER}/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}`.
- **Cloudflare** — *optional*. The default `dns_provider = "none"` uses
  sslip.io and needs no DNS provider. Switch to `cloudflare` (§7) once
  you've got a real zone.

### 2.2 Generate the Hetzner API token

1. Hetzner Cloud Console → your project → Security → API Tokens.
2. **Generate API Token** → Description `${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}-staging-tf`,
   Permissions: **Read & Write**, Save.
3. Copy the token (shown once). Stash it in a sourceable file:

   ```bash
   mkdir -p ~/.config/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}
   cat > ~/.config/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}/staging.env <<EOF
   export TF_VAR_hcloud_token="hetzner-api-token-from-console"
   EOF
   chmod 600 ~/.config/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}/staging.env
   ```

4. `rebootstrap.sh` and any new shell will pick this up automatically.

### 2.3 Create the HCP Terraform workspace

**This is the load-bearing step.** Without `execution_mode = local`,
every `terraform apply` fails with "no providers configured" (HCP runs
on its own runners that don't have your Hetzner / Cloudflare tokens).

1. https://app.terraform.io/ → sign in.
2. Pick / create the org **`${HCP_ORG}`**. (Default: same name as
   `${GITHUB_OWNER}`. Operator can override via `hcp_org` in
   `scaffold-config.yml`.)
3. **Create workspace** → **CLI-driven workflow** → name =
   **`${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}-staging`**.
4. **Settings → Execution Mode → Local → Save.** *(This is THE checklist
   item. Without it every apply will fail.)*
5. Generate an API token: choose one path:
   - **Browser flow** (recommended):
     `terraform login` → opens browser → token gets written to
     `~/.terraform.d/credentials.tfrc.json` (mode 0600).
   - **Manual**: HCP → User Settings → Tokens → Create →
     `export TF_TOKEN_app_terraform_io=<token>` in your shell rc.
6. From the repo root:

   ```bash
   cd terraform/staging
   terraform init   # pulls the providers + wires the HCP backend
   ```

### 2.4 Generate the SSH key + collect allowlist IPs

1. Generate a dedicated key (you don't want your daily-driver key on the
   server inventory):

   ```bash
   ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}-staging-operator" \
              -f ~/.ssh/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}_staging -N ""
   ```

2. Capture the pubkey:

   ```bash
   cat ~/.ssh/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}_staging.pub
   ```

   You'll paste this into `operator_ssh_pubkeys` in
   `terraform/staging/terraform.tfvars`.

3. Get your public IP for `ssh_allowed_cidrs`:

   ```bash
   curl -4 ifconfig.me   # → 203.0.113.7
   # CIDR form: 203.0.113.7/32
   ```

### 2.5 Install Terraform + lint tools

```bash
# Terraform — https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/install
sudo apt-add-repository "deb [arch=amd64] https://apt.releases.hashicorp.com $(lsb_release -cs) main"
curl -fsSL https://apt.releases.hashicorp.com/gpg | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /usr/share/keyrings/hashicorp-archive-keyring.gpg
sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get install -y terraform   # >= 1.10

# Shellcheck + python yaml for the cloud-init linter
sudo apt-get install -y shellcheck python3-yaml
```

### 2.6 Wiring Cloudflare (optional — `dns_provider = "cloudflare"`)

The default `dns_provider = "none"` uses sslip.io so the first apply
needs zero DNS setup — `terraform output -raw spa_hostname` returns
`app.5-75-123-45.sslip.io` and certs auto-provision via Caddy. See §7
for the flip procedure when you're ready for a real zone.

