## 3. Provisioning the VM

### 3.1 First apply

```bash
cd terraform/staging

# 1. Copy the tfvars template and fill in.
cp terraform.tfvars.example terraform.tfvars
# edit terraform.tfvars:
#   ssh_allowed_cidrs    = ["203.0.113.7/32"]
#   operator_ssh_pubkeys = { "alice-laptop" = "ssh-ed25519 AAAA... alice@laptop" }

# 2. Load the Hetzner token (set in §2.2).
source ~/.config/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}/staging.env

# 3. Plan + apply.
terraform plan
terraform apply
```

Expected output:

```
hcloud_ssh_key.operators["alice-laptop"]: Creation complete after 1s
hcloud_primary_ip.app: Creation complete after 2s [id=…]
hcloud_firewall.app: Creation complete after 1s [id=…]
hcloud_server.app: Creating...
hcloud_server.app: Creation complete after 24s [id=…]
hcloud_firewall_attachment.app: Creation complete after 1s
hcloud_rdns.app: Creation complete after 1s

Outputs:
api_hostname = "api.5-75-123-45.sslip.io"
spa_hostname = "app.5-75-123-45.sslip.io"
ssh_command  = "ssh deploy@5.75.123.45"
vm_ipv4      = "5.75.123.45"
vm_ipv6      = "2a01:…"
```

### 3.2 Wait for cloud-init

Cloud-init runs in the background after Hetzner's "server created"
moment. Wait for it before you ssh in for any other reason:

```bash
ssh -i ~/.ssh/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}_staging deploy@$(terraform output -raw vm_ipv4) 'cloud-init status --wait'
```

Expected: `status: done` after ~3-5 minutes. If it never converges, see
§8.1 troubleshooting.

### 3.3 Verify the VM is ready

```bash
ssh -i ~/.ssh/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}_staging deploy@$(terraform output -raw vm_ipv4) '
  set -e
  echo "docker:           $(docker --version | awk "{print \$3}" | tr -d ,)"
  stat -c "postgres dir:    %a uid=%u gid=%g (expect 700 70 70)" /var/lib/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}/db
  stat -c "secrets dir:     %a %U:%G (expect 750 root:deploy)" /etc/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}/api
  test -f /var/lib/${PROJECT_NAME_LOWER}/.bootstrap-complete && echo "bootstrap marker: OK"
'
```

All four checks must pass. If postgres dir is `0755 0 0`, the cloud-init
ran an old version — re-bootstrap (`./rebootstrap.sh --full`).

The faster wrapper:

```bash
./rebootstrap.sh        # targeted destroy + apply + wait + smoke test
./rebootstrap.sh --full # full destroy (drops the primary IP — last resort)
```

