## 6. SSH access and IP rotation

### Add a new operator pubkey

1. Append a new entry to `operator_ssh_pubkeys` in
   `terraform/staging/terraform.tfvars`:

   ```hcl
   operator_ssh_pubkeys = {
     "alice-laptop" = "ssh-ed25519 AAAA... alice@laptop"
     "bob-laptop"   = "ssh-ed25519 AAAA... bob@laptop"   # ← new
   }
   ```

2. `terraform plan` should show `+ hcloud_ssh_key.operators["bob-laptop"]`
   only (no server replacement).
3. `terraform apply`.

The new key gets injected into `/root/.ssh/authorized_keys` by Hetzner
but the load-bearing pubkey list is in cloud-init's `users:` block —
which only runs at first boot. To get the new key into
`/home/deploy/.ssh/authorized_keys` on the live VM, append it manually:

```bash
ssh deploy@<vm_ipv4> 'echo "ssh-ed25519 AAAA... bob@laptop" >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys'
```

(Or `./rebootstrap.sh` if you want everything reset clean.)

### Rotate `ssh_allowed_cidrs`

Operator moved to a new ISP, new IP. Edit `terraform.tfvars`:

```hcl
ssh_allowed_cidrs = ["198.51.100.42/32"]   # new home IP
```

`terraform plan` shows `~ hcloud_firewall.app` (in-place update). Apply,
done — no VM downtime.

